        <div class="syllabus-content">
            <div class="subject active" id="physics">
                <h3>Physics Syllabus 2025-26</h3>
                <div class="syllabus-details">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-flask"></i> Theory (70 marks, 3 hours)</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Electrostatics (14 marks): Coulomb’s law, electric field, potential, capacitors.</li>
                        <li>Current Electricity (8 marks): Ohm’s law, Kirchhoff’s laws, Wheatstone bridge.</li>
                        <li>Magnetic Effects & Magnetism (8 marks): Biot-Savart law, Ampere’s law, magnetic properties.</li>
                        <li>Electromagnetic Induction & AC (8 marks): Faraday’s laws, LCR circuits, resonance.</li>
                        <li>Electromagnetic Waves (3 marks): Properties, electromagnetic spectrum.</li>
                        <li>Optics (14 marks): Ray optics (reflection, refraction, lenses), wave optics (interference, diffraction).</li>
                        <li>Dual Nature of Matter (6 marks): Photoelectric effect, de Broglie wavelength.</li>
                        <li>Atoms & Nuclei (7 marks): Bohr model, radioactivity, nuclear reactions.</li>
                        <li>Electronic Devices (7 marks): Semiconductors, diodes, transistors, logic gates.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="syllabus-details">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-tools"></i> Practical (30 marks)</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Experiments (15 marks): Ohm’s law, meter bridge, potentiometer, LCR resonance, etc.</li>
                        <li>Project Work (10 marks): Topics like solar cells, magnetic levitation.</li>
                        <li>Practical File (5 marks): Record experiments with diagrams and observations.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="subject" id="chemistry">
                <h3>Chemistry Syllabus 2025-26</h3>
                <div class="syllabus-details">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-atom"></i> Theory (70 marks, 3 hours)</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Physical Chemistry (25 marks): Solid State, Solutions, Electrochemistry, Chemical Kinetics, Surface Chemistry.</li>
                        <li>Inorganic Chemistry (20 marks): p-Block Elements (Groups 15-18), d & f Block Elements.</li>
                        <li>Organic Chemistry (25 marks): Haloalkanes & Haloarenes, Alcohols/Phenols/Ethers, Aldehydes/Ketones/Carboxylic Acids, Amines, Biomolecules, Polymers & Chemistry in Everyday Life.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="syllabus-details">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-vial"></i> Practical (30 marks)</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Experiments (15 marks): Titration, qualitative analysis, functional group tests.</li>
                        <li>Project Work (10 marks): Environmental chemistry, organic synthesis.</li>
                        <li>Practical File (5 marks): Detailed experiment records.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="subject" id="math">
                <h3>Mathematics Syllabus 2025-26</h3>
                <div class="syllabus-details">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-calculator"></i> Theory (80 marks, 3 hours)</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Section A (65 marks): Relations & Functions, Algebra, Calculus, Probability, Vectors, 3D Geometry, Application of Integrals.</li>
                        <li>Section B (15 marks, optional): Conic Sections, 3D Geometry, Mathematical Reasoning.</li>
                        <li>Section C (15 marks, optional): Statistics, Linear Programming, Financial Mathematics.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="syllabus-details">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-project-diagram"></i> Project Work (20 marks)</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Two projects on topics like matrices, calculus, or statistics.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
